\section{How it works}{

From a \code{gdalwarp}-style request cptkirk:
\enumerate{
\item reprojects the target extent into each source's CRS to find the pixel
window that source must supply;
\item selects the overview level matching the output resolution;
\item streams just those tiles concurrently through \code{async-tiff} (one global
concurrency pool across all tiles);
\item stages them in \verb{/vsimem} and lets GDAL perform the warp, mosaicking
multiple source tiles in a single pass.
}

It reimplements none of GDAL's warp logic; it only sizes and saturates the
fetch. Sources may be local paths or \verb{http(s)://}, \verb{s3://}, \verb{gs://}, \verb{az://}
URLs.
